">Breach of Convention rights by public authority</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">22</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(1)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Civil legal services provided in relation to—</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(a)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">claim in tort, or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(b)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">a claim for damages (other than a claim in tort),</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> in respect of an act or omission by a public authority that involves a significant breach of Convention rights by the authority. </span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt; font-weight:bold">Equality</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11.5pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">43</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">(1)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">Civil legal services provided in relatio</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt">n to contravention of the Equality Act 2010 or a previous discrimination enactment.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:9pt"> </span></li></ul><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Although the Government’s proposals state that the residence test will not apply to a number of categories of case which broadly relate to an individual’s liberty, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">or </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">where the individual is particularly vulnerable</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the majority of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> areas of work carried out on behalf of our clients will remain subject to the residence test. This includes the following categories of cases which are funded under the LASPO provisions set out above:</span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Claims against the police for assault, false imprisonm</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ent and malicious prosecution (which raise issues under article 3 and 5 ECHR)</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Damages</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> claims by bereaved families arising from deaths in custody (which are frequently brought under article </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">2 ECHR as well as under the Fatal Accidents Act</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">). Although funding </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for representati</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on at</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> inquests remains outside the residence test, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">funding for </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">damages claims </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by bereaved families does not. In some cases the inquest process fails to properly address issues of concern to families and subsequent private law claims are the</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> only remaining avenue for families to bring </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">those issues before a court. In others a private law claim enables those affected by loss of a loved one, sometimes a breadwinner, to obtain compensation.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Claims against the Home Office for assault and false imp</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">risonment </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arising from detention under immigration powers</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and/or enforced removal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (which raise issues under article</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">3,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 5 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and 8 of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ECHR). Although judicial review chal</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">lenges to detention are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to fall outside the residence test, private law claims do not. Where a detainee has been</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> released or been granted bail</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">private law claim</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the only means of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> establish</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> accountability for unlawful use of </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">immigration </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">detention and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">enforcement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">powers an</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">such claims are an important check on the use</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> these powers. They</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> also provide compensation for those who have suffered lengthy detentions of months and in some cases years.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Claims for breach</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">es of the Human Rights Act 1998 and the Equality Act 2010.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">These would include</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, for example,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> claims arising from failure by the police to investigate allegat</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ions of rape</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> or domestic violence</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and claims for race discrimination against the police following arrest on the basis of racial stereotypi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng or</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> as ‘fishing ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">peditions’</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to investigate immigration status.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Damages claims by prisoners for assault and other abuses within prisons.</span></li><li style="background-color:#ffffff; font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:14.4pt; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt 46.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Judicial review challenges (other than to the lawfulness of detenti</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">on)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> many of which raise Convention rights</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. For example, challenges to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">policies on conditions of detention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, to decisions of the Independent Police Com</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">plaints Commission,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Coroners</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and of Prison Governors.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold; text-decoration:underline">Immigration Enforcement and the Residence Test </span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Those </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">who have no lawful residence </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">are subject to a raft of coercive powers of the state designed to deal with the enforcement of immigration law, i.e. powers which target the very group that would be excluded from accessing justice. These powers include the use of indefinite detention with</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">out judicial oversight </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">as well as the use of force. E</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">xamples of the litigation arising from the exercise of these powers below illustrates the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">clear </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">potential for serious human rights breaches to b</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">e carried out against the group who </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">would </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">now </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">fall to be ex</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cluded from accessing the court by the proposed reforms.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline"> </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Immigration detention</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">This firm has represented over 30 families with children in private</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> law</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> actions against the Home Office, whose claims concerned serious human rights breaches (including Articles 3, 5 and 8), false imprisonment and/or misfeasance in public office, arising from their arrest and detention under immigration powers</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. The children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">and adults concerned were commonly subjected to, in breach of the policy in place at the time, terrifying no notice dawn raids at their family home carried out by large numbers of uniformed officers, handcuffs and/or other forms of force </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">employed aga</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">inst parents in front of their children, children </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">being</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">transported in caged ‘prison’ like vans, det</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ention</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> on an indefinite basis (usually at </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Yarl’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> Wood Immigration Reception Centre) in conditions where the children could be exposed to </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">further </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">harmful and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> traumatic experiences</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. Some families were subjected to this treatment on repeated occasions.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The majority of those claims have been settled by the Home Office without admissions of liability but with damages being awarded in significant sums. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Serious</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">concerns</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">about</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">the Home Office’s policy and practice in</span><span style="font-fa