 detention itself</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, had the residence test applied at the time of these claims, the result would have been a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">wide variety of decisions on eligibility</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> for legal aid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">determining </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">which families would have been able to access t</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">he courts and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">for what length of time</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> which we co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nsider reflects</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">arbitrary </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">effect</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">proposed test.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 32.17pt; padding-left:3.83pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Those families who went on to make a fresh asylum claim or challenge asylum refusals would not fall foul of the residence test under the asylum </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">seeker’s</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> concession. In contrast those who went on </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">to make fresh human rights claims would have been excluded from legal aid.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">M</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">any of the children in these family units had meritorious applications on the basis of their birth and/or long residence in the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">United Kingdom</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Some of the families who were ultima</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tely granted leave to remain on the basis of their Article 8 applications or through Immigration Rule 395C, thereby </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">becoming lawfully resident and </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">qualifying for public funding</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> after a period of 12 months</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, would have done so long after the limitation deadl</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ine under the HRA 1998</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (12 months) had passed, and even after the limitation for false imprisonment (3 years)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> This</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> is against a background of very substantial delays in decision making in such cases, whereby the Home Office (the defendant in any proposed proceedings) elected to adopt a 5 year long </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">programme</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to clear the backlog, which continues to date. </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Those with o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n-going asylum claims would have lost public funding whilst their civil claims were on-going if their asylum applications were granted in under 12 months or if their appeal rights became exhausted.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The following family</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> would not have received public fundi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ng for their claim if the residence test had been in force: </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Case A -  </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">Family Y </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">v Home Office </span></p><p style="font-size:10pt; line-height:150%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">A family